A decision by the Finnish parliament to authorise construction of a new nuclear power unit marks the first such decision by a Western European country for some 15 years.<br>
<br>
 <br>
The decision in favour, by a margin of 107 to 92 with no abstentions, comes five months after the Finnish government voted 10 to six in favour of the initial construction application by the TVO utility. Nine years ago, a previous application to build a fifth Finnish nuclear power unit was rejected by parliament by a similar margin (107 to 90). <br>
The political background: Political and industry observers and elsewhere say today's decision reflects a gradual but ongoing change in public and political attitudes to nuclear both in Finland and elsewhere in recent years ÅEnotwithstanding political decisions in some Western European countries to plan a gradual phase-out of nuclear power. It comes against the background of growing awareness of nuclear powers potential role in mitigating the risks of climate change and ongoing improvements in industry-wide performance and safety levels world-wide. <br>
<br>
